# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Line-ending / encoding pins.
# Problem we're preventing: git's autocrlf on Windows silently rewrites
# line endings on checkout, which (a) breaks bash/.sh scripts when flipped
# to CRLF, and (b) breaks Korean Windows cmd.exe when the .cmd files lose
# their CP949+CRLF bytes. Pin everything explicitly.
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Windows batch files use CP949 (Korean ANSI) + CRLF so that Korean Windows
# cmd.exe can parse the Korean script filenames. Treat as binary so git
# never touches the bytes — no autocrlf, no encoding normalization. If you
# edit these files, save them in ANSI/CP949 with CRLF (Notepad "ANSI" on
# Korean Windows is CP949).
*.cmd   binary
*.bat   binary

# Shell scripts MUST stay LF-only or bash chokes on \r.
*.sh    text eol=lf

# PowerShell handles either, but standardize on LF for clean diffs.
*.ps1   text eol=lf

# Docs/prompt — default text, let git normalize.
*.md    text
*.html  text
*.json  text
